{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "This paper aims to advance our understanding of Heidegger's politics as it is laid bare within the ' Schwarze Hefte '.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "Yet my interest is not in Heidegger's first order political views, but rather in his conception of the political sphere per se.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "I suggest that the dominant characterisation of the political space within Heidegger's text is as a threat - to philosophy and to ontology.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "Underlying that characterisation, however, it is simultaneously possible to identify another pattern, one on which the political is itself gradually suppressed or occluded by the ontological.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "This tacit occlusion has, I suggest, a number of deeply problematic consequences.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "I will now argue that GA94 primarily characterises the political in terms of threat.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "Heidegger's view of the basic architecture of the political in GA94 is a negative one.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "The temporal dynamics and rhythms of the political sphere are thus inherently at odds, he suggests, with those of philosophy.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "The danger comes from 'the ceaseless 'politicization' of all 'sciences'.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "The threat is that politics will increasingly reconfigure philosophy in terms of its own agenda.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "For Heidegger this specific threat is ultimately a symptom of the broader trend towards technologization, and the construal of everything as a potential resource.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "The fundamental task of philosophy is to sustain, articulate and empower [ ermächtigen ] a distinctive relationship to Being [' Sein ' or ' Seyn '].",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "I argued above that the dominant presentation of the political within GA94 is as a threat - at both a general and a specific level, Heidegger presents the political as threatening philosophy, and the unique relationship to Being which philosophy sustains.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "The first strategy is one of disengagement from the public sphere.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "The second tactic is more aggressive.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "Heidegger's third, and most infamous, strategy for dealing with the threat posed by the political is to try to co-opt it, to relocate it within his own metaphysical framework.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "I am going to argue that, in important sense, Heidegger presides over an occlusion or suppression of the political, a development which has deeply problematic consequences.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU18": {
      "text": "The view manifest in both GA54 and GA94 is not one on which philosophy should direct politics, but more one on which philosophy eclipses it or occludes it.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU19": {
      "text": "It is this failure to recognise the economic and indeed the political more broadly as 'a reality with a logic and laws of its own' that I want to highlight.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU20": {
      "text": "The result, within texts like GA94, is that the political is construed using the concepts and values of ontology.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU21": {
      "text": "I have claimed that there is significant sense in which Heidegger collapses point (II) of the triangle, the political, into point (I), the ontological.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU22": {
      "text": "There are very good grounds on which to argue that, just as Heidegger reduced politics to ontology, he does the same with ethics.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU23": {
      "text": "Heidegger's treatment of authenticity exemplifies a process whereby what are loosely ethical norms, norms on the good life, become gradually reinterpreted as ontological norms, norms which are a function of our relationship to Being and of our ability to sustain a philosophy that cultivates that relationship.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
